04438nam a22006255i 9780691207278DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191994nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912072787 a10.1515/97806912072782doi  a(DE-B1597)544910  a(OCoLC)1143831541  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSCI0270002bisacsh04a591.561 aAndersson, Malte, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSexual Selection /cMalte Andersson. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (624 p.) :b10 halftones 110 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMonographs in Behavior and Ecology ;v7200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Theory of Sexual Selection -- t2. Genetic Models of Fisherian Self-Reinforcing Sexual Selection -- t3. Genetic Models of Indicator Mechanisms -- t4. Empirical Methods -- t5. Some Case Studies -- t6. Empirical Studies of Sexually Selected Traits: Patterns -- t7. Sexual Selection in Relation to Mating System and Parental Roles -- t8. Benefits of Mate Choice -- t9. Species Recognition, Sexual Selection, and Speciation -- t10. Constraints -- t11. Sexual Size Dimorphism -- t12. Weapons -- t13. Coloration and Other Visual Signals -- t14. Acoustic Signals -- t15. Chemical Signals -- t16. Alternative Mating Tactics -- t17. Sexual Selection in Plants -- t18. Sexual Selection: Conclusions and Open Questions -- tReferences -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index -- tTaxonomic Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBright colors, enlarged fins, feather plumes, song, horns, antlers, and tusks are often highly sex dimorphic. Why have males in many animals evolved more conspicuous ornaments, signals, and weapons than females? How can such traits evolve although they may reduce male survival? Such questions prompted Darwin's perhaps most scientifically controversial idea--the theory of sexual selection. It still challenges researchers today as they try to understand how competition for mates can favor the variety of sex-dimorphic traits. Reviewing theoretical and empirical work in this very active field, Malte Andersson, a leading contributor himself, provides a major up-to-date synthesis of sexual selection. The author describes the theory and its recent development; examines models, methods, and empirical tests; and identifies many unsolved problems. Among the topics discussed are the selection and evolution of mating preferences; relations between sexual selection and speciation; constraints on sexual selection; and sex differences in signals, body size, and weapons. The rapidly growing study of sexual selection in plants is also reviewed. This volume will interest students, teachers, and researchers in behavioral ecology and evolutionary biology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSexual selection in animals. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691207278zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691207278423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691207278.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK